article.description: Sue Bird scored 18 points as her Seattle Storm beat Swin Cash's Detroit Shock 72-59 Sunday night.
article.headline: Bird and Storm go 2-0 against Cash's Shock
article.linkText: In battle of ex-Huskies, Bird has bragging rights on Cash
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Sue Bird had bragging rights again.

	   Bird scored 18 points as her Seattle Storm beat Swin Cash's
Detroit Shock 72-59 Sunday night.

	   Just months ago, the two were teammates on Connecticut's 39-0
national championship team.

	   "It is strange to play against Swin, but it helps a lot that we
aren't going head-to-head,'' Bird said. "I still know every move
she's going to make. She did poke me in the eye once, but she said
she was sorry.''

	   Cash scored 15 points for the Shock (6-19).

	   The Storm won both meetings between the teams this season.

	   Lauren Jackson added 14 for Seattle before fouling out while
Kate Starbird had 13 and seven rebounds in her third game with the
Storm (13-13). Astou Ndiaye-Diatta and Elaine Powell each scored 13
for Detroit.

	   The Shock, who had a two-game winning streak ended, are 6-9
since former Pistons player Bill Laimbeer replaced Greg Williams as
head coach. The Shock opened the season 0-13 and lost 16 of their
first 17 games.

	   Seattle took control of the game with a 18-5 run late in the
first half, and led 42-25 at the intermission. Starbird came off
the bench to lead Seattle with 11 in the half, while Jackson added
10.

	   "Kate gives us something we really needed,'' Bird said. "She
can spot up and hit the outside shot, and that's what she did in
the first half.''

	   Detroit got off to a better start after the break. Back-to-back
baskets by Cash made it 45-34 with 14:36 left.

	   The Shock, though, couldn't get the lead down to single figures
until Ndiaye-Diatta's hook made it 55-47 with 5:27 to go.

	   It was still an eight-point game when Jackson and Bird hit
3-pointers on consecutive possessions to put the Storm up 69-57
with a minute to play, and Detroit never threatened again.

	   "We kind of ran out of gas mentally after playing last night,''
Laimbeer said. "They got a big lead on us and we could never get
over the hump.''
